sentences: Emily Blue (born Emily Caroline Otnes on June 28, 1994; ) is an American singer-songwriter of Norwegian descent.
section: N/A

sentences: She is known the lead singer of Champaign-based indie rock band Tara Terra.

sentences: Born and raised in Urbana, Illinois, she is now based in Chicago and Nashville.

sentences: She says her mother was the guiding figure in her home, and that she inspired her by taking a powerful female role in the household.

== Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: Blue describes the beginning of her solo music career as an accident.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: In 2016, while touring with Tara Terra and planning for the band's second studio album, Blue went through a mentally difficult time and felt the need to express her thoughts about womanhood, rape culture, and trauma.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: According to her, she packed those emotions that she felt in song form, and later produced the tracks she created and got ready to release them.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: Blue's first single, "No Pain", was released on August 6, 2016, along with the announcement of the Illinois singer-songwriter's debut EP.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: The lyrics of "No Pain" discussed rape culture in a very poignant and daring manner that caught the attention of music reviewers.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: The debut EP was eventually released on November 4, 2016.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: It was titled Another Angry Woman, with its lyrics speaking of subjects considered taboo, but conveyed with a mellow indie pop sound.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: The EP's title got its name from society's alleged response (from Blue's perspective of view) to women who were abused or assaulted.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: According to the singer, it "is a title that intends to take a critical stance on our culture's lack of empathy towards survivors".
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: The album was positively acclaimed and was labeled as "unapologetic pop" for its reluctance to stay within the limits of topics that it is considered alright to speak about.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: All the income from the album sales and merchandise for Another Angry Woman went to RACES (Rape Advocacy, Counseling, & Education Services) organization.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: On the official tracklist of the release, the five songs featured on the EP are joined by three interview tracks, titled "Anastasia", "Gene" and "Christine", all one minute in length, making this release an LP rather than an extended play.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: After the release of the album, Blue confessed that she had planned a different debut release, but scrapped it.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: Blue's post-release touring was cut short as Tara Terra planned ahead for their upcoming 2017 album, Where's Your Light?, which was announced only weeks after the release of Blue's debut non-profit album.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: During the run-up to the album, Emily Blue released two surprising tracks which showed a drastic change in the singer's genre.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: The two-sided single, "Blackberries // Rico Acid", included both tracks, and was released officially on April 7, 2017.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: It showcased Blue's musical diversity and shifted from her regular indie sound to fun, up-tempo pop.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: It also marked the beginning of Blue's collaboration with Max Perenchio.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: Blue's single "Blackberries" became largely popular on music streaming service Spotify, and currently has over 1 million streams.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: Three days after the release of the soloist's double-sided single, on April 10, 2017, the lead single from the upcoming Tara Terra album was released, titled "Like the Clothes".

sentences: Huffington Post praised the track, labeling it as the band "[showing] off their rhythmic chemistry underneath Blue's falsettos and [Colin] Althaus's bright guitar riffs."
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: The Illinois band released the rock album, which was recorded in Audiotree prior to the release of Blue's Another Angry Woman, on May 31, 2017.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===

sentences: It was described as having a harder sound than their 2014 release and received mostly positive reviews.
section: == Life and career == | === 2016–2017: Solo career and Where's Your Light? ===
